HEADWORD: Hepatize
<hw>Hep"a*tize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Hepatized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Hepatizing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Gr. <?/
to be like the liver, to be liver-colored, fr. <?/, <?/, the liver: cf.
E. <ets>hepatite</ets>, and (for sense 2) F.
<ets>h⟦eacute⟧patiser</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To impregnate with
sulphureted hydrogen gas, formerly called <xex>hepatic</xex>
gas.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On the right . . . were two wells of <qex>hepatized</qex>
water.</q> <rj><qau>Barrow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To gorge with effused matter, as the
lungs.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hepatocele</ent>⟦br⟧
